get() would also work since it checks both query parameters and form data. For the regex pattern, `<script[^>]*>.*?</script>` handles opening tags with any attributes, the content between tags, and closing tags. Using `re.IGNORECASE` ensures case-insensitive matching and `re.DOTALL` allows the dot to match newlines within script blocks.\n\nThe function should return a Response object containing the filtered content. I'll create a Flask route that takes the content parameter, applies the regex substitution with both flags, and returns the cleaned result.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4704,"cache_read_input_tokens":24095,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4704},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"475550b8-4849-4eea-94bc-916a77445667","uuid":"4b2ae68d-2ab2-4d1e-8d98-b025a234b0f4","request_id":"req_011CbdKnaC1HgdWM58PX67ZB"}
